In the eyes of many men, only two options are open to a married man who faces a risk of being beaten, abused or cheated by his wife; one, commit suicide, and the other, agree to stay in the marriage. The domestic violence advocacy groups are visited mainly by single women who need assistance. This might change if political leadership emphasises the Law on Domestic Violence, enforces it and helps to sensitize people about the importance of the law.
Domestic violence victims report reluctance from law enforcement agencies in providing specialized help. Allegations by victims that some police officers display indulgence towards perpetrators are heard with regularity. On the other hand, there are also many cases of police officers displaying commitment to support victims of violence. In the Ministry of Interior, 10 per cent of women working in police stations (1,000 officers out of total of 10,000) received a five-day certificate on prevention of domestic violence. And all domestic violence cases are to be managed together with specialized personnel in gender equality units. According to the police, there is a need for training of lawyers, prosecutors, judges, paralegals and mediators on how to address domestic violence cases.
